## The Week at a Glance

🔴 **High — Exchange Server vulnerability CVE-2026-42897 is actively patched; unpatched on-premises servers remain exposed.** June security updates are available now. Organizations still running Exchange Server 2016 or 2019 must also confirm enrollment in the Period 2 Extended Security Update (ESU) program to receive fixes.

🔴 **High — Exchange Web Services (EWS) retires in October 2026.** Microsoft has introduced an allowlist tool to help IT teams identify which applications still depend on the legacy API. Without action, those applications will stop working in roughly 90 days.

🟡 **Medium — Advanced Intune device management capabilities arrive in Microsoft 365 E3 and E5 on July 1, with tenant delivery by August 1.** No new purchase is required for eligible customers, but IT teams need time to plan adoption and communicate any workflow changes.

🟡 **Medium — Microsoft Entra ID is retiring several legacy authentication controls**, including direct Exchange ActiveSync certificate-based authentication and custom MFA controls. Organizations with affected configurations must begin migration planning now to avoid access disruptions before end of 2026.

*Sources: [Exchange Team Blog — CVE-2026-42897](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/addressing-exchange-server-may-2026-vulnerability-cve-2026-42897/ba-p/4518498) · [Exchange Team Blog — EWS Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/introducing-ewsallowedappids-preparing-for-the-final-phase-of/ba-p/4529471) · [Intune Blog — E3/E5 Packaging](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-intune-blog/it-experts-weigh-in-advanced-intune-capabilities-coming-to/ba-p/4516898)*

---

## Why This Week Matters

Three deadlines converge this quarter that carry real business and compliance consequence. A patched but still-circulating Exchange Server vulnerability, a hard API retirement in October, and an authentication modernization wave all require decisions that span security, IT, and budget. At the same time, Microsoft is shipping the broadest wave of AI agent tools in the platform's history, and early movers on governance controls will be better positioned than those who wait. The one thing leadership must understand: the AI productivity gains arriving this week come with new data access risks that your compliance and security teams need visibility into before those agents touch sensitive content at scale.

*Sources: [Microsoft Entra Blog — Entra ID Security Updates](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-what-organizations-need-to/ba-p/4522024) · [Microsoft Security Blog — AI Accelerating Cyberattacks](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/ai-is-accelerating-cyberattacks-here-s-how-to-stay-ahead/ba-p/4528592)*

