## If You Take No Action

**Exchange Server CVE-2026-42897 remains unpatched.** Any employee who opens a specially crafted email in Outlook Web Access on an unpatched server is exposed to arbitrary code execution in their browser session. An attacker who triggers this could capture credentials, session tokens, or initiate further lateral movement inside your network. This is a confirmed, publicly disclosed vulnerability with a patch already available. Delay increases your exposure window and may void cyber insurance coverage for incidents traced to unpatched systems.

**EWS-dependent applications stop working in October 2026.** When Microsoft disables EWS access in Exchange Online, any application, workflow, or integration that has not migrated to Microsoft Graph will fail silently or with errors. Depending on what those systems do, the consequences range from disrupted shared calendars to failed compliance data exports to broken clinical scheduling workflows. The new EWSAllowedAppIDs tool buys time by letting IT allowlist known applications temporarily, but it does not extend the deadline. Organizations that have not inventoried and begun migration by late summer will face a crisis, not a planned transition.

**Legacy authentication retirements create access gaps.** If organizations do not migrate mobile devices off EAS certificate-based authentication before end of 2026, those devices will lose email access without warning when Microsoft enforces the change. For organizations in regulated industries where employees rely on mobile email for patient care, financial transactions, or field operations, an unplanned authentication failure is both an operational and a compliance event.

*Sources: [Exchange Team Blog — CVE-2026-42897](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/addressing-exchange-server-may-2026-vulnerability-cve-2026-42897/ba-p/4518498) · [Exchange Team Blog — EWS Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/introducing-ewsallowedappids-preparing-for-the-final-phase-of/ba-p/4529471) · [Exchange Team Blog — EAS CBA Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/retirement-of-direct-exchange-activesync-certificate-based/ba-p/4517896)*